info       = "<html><body><table><tr><td>Drug:</td><td>N07BB02</td></tr><td>route:</td><td>oral</td></tr><tr><td>n-compartments</td><td>1</td></tr></table><p>Calcium carbimide is an alcohol deterrent drug used as an adjunct in the treatment of chronic alcoholism. It works by inhibiting the enzyme acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, causing unpleasant effects when alcohol is consumed. It is an alternative to disulfiram. The drug is not widely used today and is not approved in many countries.</p><h4>Pharmacokinetics</h4><p>No published pharmacokinetic data for calcium carbimide has been found in the literature. Below values are theoretical estimates for an adult based on oral administration and analogy with similar drugs (e.g., disulfiram).</p><h4>References</h4><ol><li><p>Obach, R, et al., &amp; Domenech, J (1991). Pharmacokinetics and oral bioavailability of carbimide in man. <i>Biopharmaceutics &amp; drug disposition</i> 12(6) 425–434. DOI:<a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1002/bdd.2510120604\">10.1002/bdd.2510120604</a>  PUBMED:<a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1932606/\">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1932606</a></p></li><li><p>Jones, AW (1995). Measuring and reporting the concentration of acetaldehyde in human breath. <i>Alcohol and alcoholism (Oxford, Oxfordshire)</i> 30(3) 271–285. PUBMED:<a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7545981/\">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7545981</a></p></li><li><p>Benzi, G, &amp; Ceci, A (2001). Creatine as nutritional supplementation and medicinal product. <i>The Journal of sports medicine and physical fitness</i> 41(1) 1–10. PUBMED:<a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11317142/\">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11317142</a></p></li></ol></body></html>",
